3 Import Datasets and Create Tables

Important: You will need to complete the following steps multiple times, once for each required dataset!

To be able to read datasets in using sparks read in functions, you must upload the data to its FileStore.

  1. Click on the create (plus sign) button again and select âTableâ. This will take you to the create new table tool.

  1. Either:
  • Click on the âFilesâ box to open up a file explorer browser. Navigate to the course materials âdataâ folder and upload the csv file.
  • Drag and drop the dataset into the âFilesâ box.

Once it is uploaded, a note will appear below that the file was uploaded to â/FileStore/tables/.â which will be the filepath used to read the data in later.

  1. Now that the data is uploaded, SQL tables can be created using the âCreate Table with UIâ button.

This will prompt you to select your cluster from a dropdown, and hence click âPreview Tableâ. An example of the schools_data is shown below.

There are numerous options available for how the table should be stored.

  • You should change the table name - usually, â_csvâ is attached to the dataset name.
  • You should tick âFirst row is headerâ, as this is not always the case by default.
  • You should manually check the type of each column with the dropdowns beneath them, or allow spark to do this by ticking âInfer schemaâ.

Finally, click âCreate Tableâ. The final dataset and its schema are shown for you to review.

  1. To check the dataset, select âCatalogâ in the left hand menu.

4 Create a Coding Notebook

  • Equations

  1. Click the create (plus sign) button again and select âNotebookâ.
